Written April 25, 2017
TravellingVolup
United Kingdom280 contributions
4.0 of 5 bubbles
Fascinating But More Should Be Invested In Upkeep
We spent a lovely hour and a half at this interesting and nationally important museum. Unfortunately, we didn't have the time this trip to visit, My Son, so opted to visit this collection of artifacts. It is housed in a building originally built in 1919 and later extended to house more objects. My initial reaction to the building itself was one of sadness as it seems more could be done to preserve such important historical evidence. I noted the reception area even lacked proper blinds; however, once we purchased our English audio guides ( which as others have stated I highly recommend for 20,000 VND) I was transported back in time. It didn't matter at all that the place was busy with individual and group guides chattering away. The informative audio guide was excellent value and made the journey through this small, but important museum worthwhile. I would suggest you bring your own earplugs because: 1) I had to go through five to get one with both ears giving sound and 2) It was very clear that the earbuds are not cleaned or sterilised as the lovely young lady tried all of the five in her ears before handing the ones that did work to me! Fortunately, I am not overly fussed about things like this, but others might be! I was impressed by the collection and interested in their historical significance. Especially, the links and influence between countries, including Greece on the images themselves. It is well worth a visit and despite others saying it lacks air-conditioning, there were several large and powerful fans that kept the building cool and comfortable.
Written April 9, 2017
